{{Distinguish|Mensural notation}}
[[File:Josquin Domine ne in furore.svg|thumb|right|350px|Beginning of psalm motet "Domine, ne in furore" by [[Josquin des Prez]], typeset in ''{{Lang|de|Mensurstrich}}'' layout. Note how the same dotted-[[Minim (music)|minim]] [[Motif (music)|motive]] may occur either within a bar or stretching across a bar boundary. ([[:File:Josquin Domine ne in furore.pdf|Full score]]; {{audio|Josquin Domine ne in furore.mid|listen}})]]
'''{{Lang|de|Mensurstrich}}''' (''plural'' '''{{Lang|de|Mensurstriche}}''') is a German term used in [[musical notation]] to denote a [[Bar (music)|barline]] that is drawn between [[staff (music)|staves]], but not across them. It is typically seen in modern editions of [[Medieval music|Medieval]] and [[Renaissance music|Renaissance]] vocal [[polyphony]], where it is intended to allow modern performers the convenience of barlines without having them interfere with the music, which was originally written without barlines. In most cases [[note value]]s are allowed to cross over a {{Lang|de|Mensurstrich}} without requiring a [[tie (music)|tie]].

The convention of the {{Lang|de|Mensurstrich}} was introduced by German [[musicologist]]s such as [[Heinrich Besseler]] in the 1920s and became common in editorial practice by the mid-20th century.<ref>{{cite book|first=Werner|last=Breig|chapter=Die Editionsgeschichte der ''Geistlichen Chormusik'' von Heinrich Schütz|editor-first=Helga|editor-last=Lühning|title=Musikedition: Mittler zwischen Wissenschaft und musikalischer Praxis|location=Tübingen|publisher=Niemeyer|year=2002|pages=237–277}}</ref> It is frequently applied in academic editions of 15th and 16th century music such as those in the multi-volume ''[[Corpus mensurabilis musicae]]'' published by the American Institute of Musicology.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grier|first=James|title=The Critical Editing of Music: History, Method and Practice|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1996|pages=165f.}}</ref>

A few modern composers (such as [[Hugo Distler]], whose vocal music is reminiscent of Renaissance vocal polyphony) have made a practice of using it in their music in order to minimize the regularity of [[meter (music)|meter]].

